## Quality-Length Trimming

### Not known what library prep kit the sequencing center used -- don't know adapter sequences 
### For now, I'll filter to reads >75bp and run trimmomatic with standard Nextera PE adapters

#### Length filtering in shell:


```python
for i in *fastq.gz ; do zcat $i | awk 'BEGIN {FS = "\t" ; OFS = "\n"} {header = $0 ; getline seq ; getline qheader ; getline qseq ; if (length(seq) >= 75) {print header, seq, qheader, qseq}}' > "$i".75bp.fastq

```

#### Quality/adapter trim with trimmomatic


```python
while read i ; do java -jar ~/bin/trimmomatic.jar PE -threads 8 "$i".R1.fastq.gz.75bp.fastq "$i".R2.fastq.gz.75bp.fastq "$i".R1.paired.fq.gz "$i".R1.unpaired.fq.gz "$i".R2.paired.fq.gz "$i".R2.unpaired.fq.gz ILLUMINACLIP:/home/ps997/bin/trimmomatic/adapters/NexteraPE-PE.fa:2:30:10 LEADING:3 TRAILING:3 SLIDINGWINDOW:4:15 MINLEN:75 ; done < Isoetes_GBS_samples.txt
                                    
```

##### Quality-length trim results
Everything looking good -- eliminating reads < 75 bp drops roughly 5-10% of reads, then ~97% of length-filtered reads pass trimmomatic as paired

##### FASTQC results of quality filtered reads 
Still show nucleotide regularity at first few positions -- R1 files have TGCAG, which was our restriction enzyme cut sequence -- apparently the demultiplexer did not remove this
R2 files tend to end with CGG -- unsure of its origin

```python
axes.plot(etable.deltaK, color="steelblue", marker="o");
axes.y.spine.style = {"stroke": "steelblue"}

# set x labels
axes.x.ticks.locator = toyplot.locator.Explicit(range(len(etable.index)), etable.index)
axes.x.label.text = "K (N ancestral populations)"
```

```python
# select K
for k in range(2,11):
    table = struct.get_clumpp_table(k)

    # sort list by columns
    # table.sort_values(by=list(range(k)), inplace=True)

    # or, sort by a list of names (here taken from imap)
    import itertools
    onames = list(itertools.chain(*imap.values()))
    table = table.loc[onames]

    # build barplot
    canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=250)
    axes = canvas.cartesian(bounds=("10%", "90%", "10%", "45%"))
    axes.bars(table)

    # add labels to x-axis
    ticklabels = [i for i in table.index.tolist()]
    axes.x.ticks.locator = toyplot.locator.Explicit(labels=ticklabels)
    axes.x.ticks.labels.angle = -60
    axes.x.ticks.show = True
    axes.x.ticks.labels.offset = 10
    axes.x.ticks.labels.style = {"font-size": "6px"}
```

```python
import ipyrad.analysis as ipa
import pandas as pd
import toyplot
import toyplot.pdf

# the path to your .snps.hdf5 database file
data = "/Users/Peter/Li-Lab-BTI/peter/Broxton.snps.hdf5"


# group individuals into populations
imap = {"Arch_Cave": ["Arch_Cave_1", "Arch_Cave_2", "Arch_Cave_3", "Arch_Cave_4", "Arch_Cave_5"],\
    "Arch_Cave_East": ["Arch_Cave_East_1", "Arch_Cave_East_2", "Arch_Cave_East_3", "Arch_Cave_East_4", "Arch_Cave_East_5"],\
    "Corbitt_Tract": ["Corbitt_Tract_10", "Corbitt_Tract_11", "Corbitt_Tract_12", "Corbitt_Tract_1", "Corbitt_Tract_6", "Corbitt_Tract_7", "Corbitt_Tract_8", "Corbitt_Tract_9a", "Corbitt_Tract_9b"],\
    "Corbitt_Tract_Mid": ["Corbitt_Tract_Mid_1", "Corbitt_Tract_Mid_2", "Corbitt_Tract_Mid_3", "Corbitt_Tract_Mid_4", "Corbitt_Tract_Mid_5"],\
    "Flat_Tub_13_S": ["Flat_Tub_13_S_1", "Flat_Tub_13_S_2", "Flat_Tub_13_S_4", "Flat_Tub_13_S_5", "Flat_Tub_13_S_6"],\
    "Flat_Tub_789": ["Flat_Tub_789_1", "Flat_Tub_789_2", "Flat_Tub_789_3", "Flat_Tub_789_4", "Flat_Tub_789_5"],\
    "Ricketson_Tract_SW": ["Ricketson_Tract_SW_1", "Ricketson_Tract_SW_2", "Ricketson_Tract_SW_3", "Ricketson_Tract_SW_4", "Ricketson_Tract_SW_5"],\
    "South_of_Sawdust": ["South_of_Sawdust_10", "South_of_Sawdust_2a", "South_of_Sawdust_2b", "South_of_Sawdust_3", "South_of_Sawdust_4", "South_of_Sawdust_7", "South_of_Sawdust_9"],\
}

# require that 75% of samples have data in each group
minmap = {i: 0.75 for i in imap}

# init pca object with input data and (optional) parameter options
pca = ipa.pca(
    data=data,
    imap=imap,
    minmap=minmap,
    mincov=0.75,
    impute_method="sample",
)

# run the PCA analysis
pca.run()

# store the PC axes as a dataframe
df = pd.DataFrame(pca.pcaxes[0], index=pca.names)

# write the PC axes to a CSV file
df.to_csv("pca_analysis.csv")

# show the first ten samples and the first 10 PC axes
df.iloc[:10, :10].round(2)

# plot PC axes 0 and 1
pca.draw(0, 1);

# plot PC axes 0 and 2
pca.draw(0, 2);

# plot PC axes 1 and 2
pca.draw(1, 2);
```

```python
# init pca object with input data and (optional) parameter options
pca = ipa.pca(
    data=data,
    imap=imap,
    minmap=minmap,
    mincov=0.75,
    impute_method="sample",
)

# run the PCA analysis
pca.run()

# store the PC axes as a dataframe
df = pd.DataFrame(pca.pcaxes[0], index=pca.names)

# write the PC axes to a CSV file
df.to_csv("pca_analysis.csv")

# show the first ten samples and the first 10 PC axes
df.iloc[:10, :10].round(2)

# plot PC axes 0 and 1
pca.draw(0, 1);

# plot PC axes 0 and 2
pca.draw(0, 2);

# plot PC axes 1 and 2
pca.draw(1, 2);
```

# Using DADA to filter and cluster PacBio reads instead of PURC


Demultiplex with PURC, then create separate fastq's for each sample and run through DADA


```python
## Start in R
library(dada2);packageVersion("dada2")
library(Biostrings); packageVersion("Biostrings")
library(ShortRead); packageVersion("ShortRead")
library(ggplot2); packageVersion("ggplot2")
library(reshape2); packageVersion("reshape2")
library(gridExtra); packageVersion("gridExtra")
library(phyloseq); packageVersion("phyloseq")
library(DECIPHER)

### First orient reads
readsDB <- readDNAStringSet("~/Desktop/DADA/JSS1_2017_reads_of_insert.fastq", format="fastq",
                            nrec=-1L, skip=0L, seek.first.rec=FALSE,
                            use.names=TRUE, with.qualities=TRUE)
readsDB
oriented.reads <- OrientNucleotides(readsDB,
                                    reference = c(3,4,110897,110898),
                                    type = "sequences",
                                    orientation = "all",
                                    threshold = 0.05,
                                    verbose = TRUE,
                                    processors = 4)
oriented.reads
writeXStringSet(oriented.reads,"~/Desktop/DADA/JSS1_2017_reads_of_insert.oriented.fastq" , append=FALSE,
                compress=FALSE, compression_level=NA, format="fastq")
### Now split reads into samples in shell/python

# Run PURC to demultiplex
/Applications/Phylogenetics/purc.py config_LFY_JSS1_2017-2020rerun.txt

# Use demultiplexed annotation file to split fastq
# In shell:
grep ">"  purc_run_LFY_JSS1_2017-2020rerun_3_annotated.fa > annotated.names.tmp
sed -i 's/>//' annotated.names.tmp
sed -i 's/p0_/p0\//' annotated.names.tmp
sed -i 's/_ccs/\/ccs' annotated.names.tmp
mv annotated.names.tmp annotated.names.txt

# In python:
from Bio import SeqIO

demultiplexDict = {}
mapfile = open("PURC_annotation_seqnames.txt", "r")
for line in mapfile:
	id = line.strip("\n").split("\t")[0]
	seqName = line.strip("\n").split("\t")[1]
	try:
		demultiplexDict[id].append(seqName)
	except KeyError:
		demultiplexDict[id] = [seqName]
mapfile.close()
seqDict = SeqIO.index("JSS1_2017_reads_of_insert.fastq", "fastq")
for key in demultiplexDict.keys():
	outfile = open("%s.fastq" % key, "w")
	for seqname in demultiplexDict[key]:
		try:
			record = seqDict[seqname]
			SeqIO.write(record, outfile, "fastq")
		except KeyError:
			print("%s not found in input seqeunce file" % seqname)
	outfile.close()

    

# Should result in many new fastqs named by the first column of annotated.names.txt. Shouldn't have any error message, if you get error the annotation and sequence file have different sequences (sequence names)
# Move new sample fastqs into ~/Desktop/DADA/seqs/

# ### After reads split continue here in R
path1 <- "~/Desktop/DADA/seqs"
path.out <- "Figures/"
path.rds <- "RDS/"
theme_set(theme_bw())

fns1 <- list.files(path1, pattern="fastq", full.names=TRUE)
lens.fn <- lapply(fns1, function(fn) nchar(getSequences(fn)))
lens <- do.call(c, lens.fn)
hist(lens, 100)

# Filter reads by length, quality and expected errors
filts1 <- file.path(path1, "noprimers", "filtered", basename(fns1))
track1 <- filterAndTrim(fns1, filts1, minQ=3, minLen=1000, maxLen=1200, maxN=0, rm.phix=FALSE, maxEE=5)
track1

filtered.path <- "~/Desktop/DADA/seqs/noprimers/filtered"
flts1 <- fns1 <- list.files(filtered.path, pattern="fastq", full.names=TRUE)
lens.fn <- lapply(flts1, function(fn) nchar(getSequences(fn)))
lens <- do.call(c, lens.fn)
hist(lens, 100)

drp1 <- derepFastq(filts1, verbose=TRUE)
err1 <- learnErrors(drp1, errorEstimationFunction=PacBioErrfun, BAND_SIZE=32, multithread=TRUE)
#saveRDS(err1, file.path(path.rds, "PacBio_err1.rds")) # these fail for me but don't think they're necessary
plotErrors(err1)
dd2 <- dada(drp1, err=err1, BAND_SIZE=32, multithread=TRUE, pool="pseudo")
#saveRDS(dd2, file.path(path.rds, "PacBio_dd2.rds")) # these fail for me but don't think they're necessary
cbind(filtered=track1[,2], denoised=sapply(dd2, function(x) sum(x$denoised)))
st2 <- makeSequenceTable(dd2); dim(st2)
bim2 <- isBimeraDenovo(st2, minFoldParentOverAbundance=3.5, multithread=TRUE)
table(bim2)
sum(st2[,bim2])/sum(st2)

for (sample in names(dd2)) {
  seqList <- getSequences(dd2[[sample]])
  i <- 1
  while (i <= length(seqList)){
    seqName <- as.character(paste(">", sample, "_ASV", i, sep = ""))
    write(seqName, file="JSS1_DADA_ASVs.fasta", append = TRUE)
    write(seqList[[i]], file="JSS1_DADA_ASVs.fasta", append = TRUE)
    i <- i+1
      }
}
```
